00:10:23.050 --> 00:10:26.440
Aging isn't just
limited to Asia Pacific.

00:10:26.440 --> 00:10:29.210
It's a worldwide
phenomena, aging societies.

00:10:29.210 --> 00:10:32.370
So many of the European
countries

00:10:32.370 --> 00:10:37.790
across Asia Pacific including
Japan, Korea, Singapore, Taiwan,

00:10:37.790 --> 00:10:41.250
China itself because of some of
their policies over the years,

00:10:41.250 --> 00:10:44.540
some of the South American
countries like Argentina

00:10:44.540 --> 00:10:47.980
and Chile, and some of the
Middle Eastern countries, too,

00:10:47.980 --> 00:10:51.500
and North African countries
such as Algeria and Iran,

00:10:51.500 --> 00:10:53.640
all aging quite rapidly.

00:10:53.640 --> 00:10:57.010
And over the coming years
going to be approaching 25-30%

00:10:57.010 --> 00:10:59.290
or even 40% in Japan's case,

00:10:59.290 --> 00:11:02.770
of the population being
65 years and older.

00:11:02.770 --> 00:11:05.470
So significance aside
all challenge,

00:11:05.470 --> 00:11:08.460
and for many countries
the risk is

00:11:08.460 --> 00:11:12.320
of becoming older before they
become developed or richer.

00:11:12.320 --> 00:11:16.260
So for a country like
Japan or Korea or some

00:11:16.260 --> 00:11:19.620
of the European ones which are
very successful economically,

00:11:19.620 --> 00:11:23.080
have public health
infrastructure in place,

00:11:23.080 --> 00:11:26.730
their much in better
circumstances for aging society

00:11:26.730 --> 00:11:29.640
than a developing country that
doesn't have public health

00:11:29.640 --> 00:11:33.160
yet or, indeed, has a
relatively low GDP as some

00:11:33.160 --> 00:11:34.460
of the developing countries do.

00:11:34.460 --> 00:11:38.830
We'll see in a little bit, too,
it's also a phenomenon in Africa

00:11:38.830 --> 00:11:42.460
where some of the African
countries projected not

00:11:42.460 --> 00:11:45.160
to have 40% of their
population, but up to 20%

00:11:45.160 --> 00:11:52.210
of their population age 65
and older by the year 2050.

00:11:52.210 --> 00:11:57.440
So aging oftentimes is depicted
as homogenous, or one view,

00:11:57.440 --> 00:12:00.010
of what aging is or
what aging means.

00:12:00.010 --> 00:12:02.440
But, really, aging
is quite varied.

00:12:02.440 --> 00:12:08.350
Many seniors now and over
the years quite active well

00:12:08.350 --> 00:12:11.170
into their 60s, 70s,
80s, and 90s --

00:12:11.170 --> 00:12:14.030
active in society,
active working.

00:12:14.030 --> 00:12:17.810
Other seniors, more and more,
are trying to age in place

00:12:17.810 --> 00:12:20.150
and there's different policies
around the world for that --

00:12:20.150 --> 00:12:23.060
to be able to stay living
in their homes longer

00:12:23.060 --> 00:12:25.440
as a way to stay engaged.

00:12:25.440 --> 00:12:28.950
But also too many seniors
do have fragility issues

00:12:28.950 --> 00:12:31.550
and then some also
have memory issues.

00:12:31.550 --> 00:12:34.570
So very broad range of
seniors and a very broad range

00:12:34.570 --> 00:12:38.280
of technologies which are
applicable to each of the groups

00:12:38.280 --> 00:12:42.580
or circumstances of the seniors.

00:12:42.580 --> 00:12:45.750
And we'll also see that, how the
technologies are being tailored,

00:12:45.750 --> 00:12:48.700
including fostered and
promoted by the U.S. Government

00:12:48.700 --> 00:12:52.620
for different types or
circumstances of seniors.

00:12:52.620 --> 00:12:58.610
One thing which is a
major challenge worldwide,

00:12:58.610 --> 00:13:00.920
and we'll talk about some of
the other challenges of aging

00:13:00.920 --> 00:13:05.030
in addition to health, is
this question of poverty.

00:13:05.030 --> 00:13:09.070
Seniors oftentimes, and in many
countries, don't have pensions

00:13:09.070 --> 00:13:10.980
or something has
happened to the pension

00:13:10.980 --> 00:13:13.450
such as municipal bankruptcy,

00:13:13.450 --> 00:13:16.740
or a country doesn't have
a pension system yet,

00:13:16.740 --> 00:13:19.680
and when the senior's no longer
working then then don't have a

00:13:19.680 --> 00:13:20.980
regular income.

00:13:20.980 --> 00:13:22.430
One other thing which
is happening

00:13:22.430 --> 00:13:25.190
in many countries is
a change of culture.

00:13:25.190 --> 00:13:29.010
So many countries traditionally
have had a cultural support

00:13:29.010 --> 00:13:33.300
system where the young care
for and support the parents

00:13:33.300 --> 00:13:35.170
and the grandparents
and the elderly.

00:13:35.170 --> 00:13:38.260
That is changing in
many countries now,

00:13:38.260 --> 00:13:42.500
including in Asia Pacific
where sometimes the youth moves

00:13:42.500 --> 00:13:45.450
to the larger cities,
but the seniors remain

00:13:45.450 --> 00:13:49.860
in the rural areas, and there's
not the contact or support

00:13:49.860 --> 00:13:52.880
that that might have
been in previous decades.

00:13:52.880 --> 00:13:56.470
One other issue, too, is with
the rapidly aging society,

00:13:56.470 --> 00:13:57.890
instead of having six or seven

00:13:57.890 --> 00:14:03.170
or eight younger people
supporting the seniors

00:14:03.170 --> 00:14:07.240
through pensions or care, in
some countries it's moving

00:14:07.240 --> 00:14:10.510
to three to one or two to one,

00:14:10.510 --> 00:14:13.700
two people in the workforce
supporting one senior person.

00:14:13.700 --> 00:14:17.600
So the support system
may or may not be there

00:14:17.600 --> 00:14:21.300
from country to country.

00:14:21.300 --> 00:14:24.350
So aging varies across
the world, and aging, too,

00:14:24.350 --> 00:14:28.540
varies across the U.S.
but by county and city.

